<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-612-008  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 612 008.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 2 1990 v24 n27 p57(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Phone companies strike up bandwidth. (Raynet Corp. and AT and Tlaunch fiber optic pilot projects)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Savage, J.A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Raynet and AT and T are conducting pilot projects to test theviability of bringing high-bandwidth fiber optic cabling into thehome market.andP;  The Raynet project involves a 100-house installationin Lynnfield, MA, while the rival AT and T pilot involves 2,000homes.andP;  The Raynet project will utilize trunk line fiber optics, aSubscriber Interface Unit at the curb for each four to eight homesand standard copper wiring for the curb-to-home connection.andP;  Itwill cost about $1,200 per subscriber.andP;  For this price, the userwill receive enough optical fiber bandwidth to support suchapplications as HDTV or a graphics-intensive home workstation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Raynet Corp. (innovations)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (innovations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Telephone companiesFiber opticsPilot ProjectsBandwidthApplicationsCost of CommunicationsCommunications Service Suppliers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>